  "prompt": "Why was World War 1 fought?",
  "response": "World War 1 (1914-1918) was primarily triggered by a complex web of factors:\n\n1. Nationalism\n- Growing nationalist sentiments in European countries\n- Desire for territorial expansion and global power\n\n2. Militarism\n- Arms race between European powers\n- Countries building large military forces and preparing for potential conflict\n\n3. Imperialism\n- Competition for colonial territories and global influence\n- Tensions between major European powers like Britain, Germany, France, and Austria-Hungary\n\n4. Alliance Systems\n- Complex network of military alliances divided Europe into two main camps:\n- Triple Alliance: Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy\n- Triple Entente: Britain, France, Russia\n\n5. Immediate Trigger\n- Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary in Sarajevo by a Serbian nationalist in June 1914\n- This event sparked a chain reaction of declarations of war between allied countries\n\n6. Underlying Tensions\n- Long-standing rivalries between European powers\n- Desire to maintain or challenge the existing balance of power in Europe\n\nThe war ultimately involved many countries worldwide, becoming a global conflict that resulted in massive loss of life and significant geopolitical changes.",
